{
  "text": " The peptide that finally shows up in tissue repair cases, no protocol touches. HHS flagged peptides as a research priority this year. In clinical practice, this space has been active for a decade. One compound keeps coming back. Not because of the hype, because the pattern of response keeps showing up in the cases that don't fit the standard protocol. The compound is BPC157, pentadecopeptide, 15 amino acids, derived from a protective sequence in gastric juice. What the research keeps returning to is the same three clinical surfaces. Gut, mucosal support, soft tissue repair, and recovery signaling in cases where the standard protocol has plateaued. In practice, I reach for infiniwell because they offer two release profiles. The delayed release oral form for gut lining cases, the rapid release form for soft tissue and recovery cases, same active compound, different delivery targets, 15 amino acids, a protective sequence the stomach already makes. The body recognizes it before the research catches up. Not a fix, a variable worth testing when a case has plateaued in a predictable place. Full pattern breakdown at tr.e slash owq7fm. Type it.",
